omments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 20 Dec 2012 01:46:26 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"Calendar Insights";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"calendar";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"gregorian calendar";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"mayan calendar";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=23969";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:309:"People, throw out your diaries! Rid yourselves of your calendars! The end is nigh! The world will end on December 21st. Weâre reaching the cataclysm: the 21st ofÂ December, 2012 will bring about the end of all things. Maybe. Thatâs all &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/the-end-is-nigh-maybe/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3453:"<p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-23970" title="Photo: CreativeCommons &gt;Flickr&gt; Some rights reserved by CarlosVanVegas" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/mayancalendarphoto.jpg" alt="Photo: CreativeCommons &gt;Flickr&gt; Some rights reserved by CarlosVanVegas" width="500" height="375" /></p>\n<p>People, throw out your diaries! Rid yourselves of your calendars! The end is nigh! The world will end on December 21st. Weâre reaching the cataclysm: the 21st ofÂ December, 2012 will bring about the end of all things. Maybe.</p>\n<p>Thatâs all pretty tongue-in-cheek. What happens on the 21st of December 2012 is that we reach the end of one cycle in the old Mayan calendar. People seem to have gotÂ pretty exercised about this, with one poll, as reported by Reuters, showing that 1 in 10 of us are anxious about the world ending on December 21st.</p>\n<p>Of course, there isnât any reason to be worried about this actually happening, as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_calendar" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a> entry on the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_calendar" target="_blank">Mayan calandar</a> makes pretty clear. All thatâs happening isÂ that weâre reaching the end of this b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun, and a b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun is nothing more than a way of representing 144,000 days from the act of creation thatâs supposed to haveÂ occurred in 3114BC. In the Mayan calendar, the date on what we call the 29th of December is 12.19.19.17.18. The date on the 21st? 13.0.0.0.0!</p>\n<p>Whilst to our eyes this is an unusual way of representing time, thereâs no reason at all to worry about it. Itâs a bit like worrying that there will be an apocolypseÂ because weâve reached the end of a decade, or the end of a century, or the end of a milleniumâalthough plenty of people managed to worry about that, too!</p>\n<p>Of course, this is hardly the first time that calendars have caused a stir. In 1752, Great Britain adopted the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregorian_Calendar" target="_blank">Gregorian Calendar</a>. This required a re-adjustment of dates andÂ so it was that Wednesday 2nd September was followed by Thursday 14th September. Although tales of riots and violence seem to be somewhat overstated, nonetheless itÂ was certainly an important social and political upheaval.</p>\n<p>So why do we get so vexed about these dates in time if, in fact, theyâre actually insignificant? Well, hereâs one thought. Thereâs a natural tendency to get spooked byÂ things that we donât understand. The unknown can be pretty scary sometimes And for all of our advancements in measuring and thinking about time, it still seems to meÂ that the following quote from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustine%27s_Confessions" target="_blank">Augustineâs Confessions</a> (Book 11, chapter 14) rings true: âWhat, then, is time? If no one asks me, I know what it is. If I wish to explainÂ it to him who asks me, I do not know.â Maybeâjust maybeâthat sense of mystery that still shrouds the concept of time, coupled to the striking simplicity of some of theÂ numbers involved (13.0.0.0.0 in the Mayan case, and 2000 in the other Iâve talked about) come together to generate a sense of unease. Whatever the explanation forÂ these unfounded concerns, have a very happy end of this <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%27ak%27tun" target="_blank">b&#8217;ak&#8217;tun</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:42:"http://time.ly/the-end-is-nigh-maybe/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"Life Flashes Before Your Eyes";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 06 Dec 2012 15:39:30 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=22749";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:337:"Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in aÂ linear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal. Itâs that familiar drudgeÂ of one thing after another! But there &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5352:"<p>Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in aÂ linear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal.</p>\n<p>Itâs that familiar drudgeÂ of one thing after another! But there are some rare experiences that areÂ very different. These are experiences where all (or at least many) of the events of our lives âflashÂ before our eyesâ seemingly all at once. These cases, unlike those that we normally experience,Â seem to be ones where the regular succession of events is interrupted and we experience wholeÂ sections of our past lives in a single instant (or similarly short interval of time).</p>\n<p>In many ways these experiences seem really strange. Not only are these cases where peopleÂ report re-living events from the past, they are sometimes also associated with a sense of timeÂ slowing down and everything becoming clear. Of course, it seems peculiar to say that time reallyÂ slows down in these cases, or that we really can experience all of those events from our lives.Â After all, if those events took so many years to occur, how can I possibly experience them in theÂ very brief time it takes for Â my life to flash before my eyes?</p>\n<p>Strange as they may be, these experiences are reasonably well documented (as a quick internetÂ search reveals!) in a range of different cultures. Whatâs striking form our own culture is thatÂ these kinds of experience (of many events flashing before our eyes) are generally supposed to beÂ closely associated with ânear death experiencesâ, other features of which include an awareness ofÂ being dead, moving through a tunnel and communicating with light.</p>\n<div id="attachment_22753" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-22753" title="MikeBaird" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/MikeBaird1-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo by Mike Baird, courtesy of Creative Commons</p></div>\n<p>But in fact, in scientific studies, it doesnât seem that there is such a close association. This experience of events where oneâs life seeming to flash by all at once is sometimes referred to as âlife review&#8217;and, in one study at least, was only present in 13% of Near Death Experiences.(1) One other interesting feature of near death experiences is that although patients most viewÂ themselves as being close to death, one study showed that of 58 such patients only 28 were in factÂ in a condition such that, had they not had medical intervention, they would have died.(2)</p>\n<p>Historically, such experiences as having oneâs life flash before oneâs eyes have taken on aÂ good deal of religious significance and continue to do so today for some people. Even wereÂ such experiences to not in fact be caused by any supranatural involvement, this would beÂ unsurprising. Instances of near death experiences frequently lead to people re-examining theirÂ lives and changing the way that they do things.(3)</p>\n<p>Increasingly, though, thereâs evidence that near death experiences themselves can be explainedÂ without recourse to any supranatural being. Indeed, many of the features of near deathÂ experiences can be triggered simply by stimulating particular regions of the brain.(4) Similarly,Â there are plausible explanations of the mechanisms by which near death experiences in generalÂ might be brought about by low CO2 levels in the bloodstream.(5)</p>\n<p>But, be that as it may, there remains a particular fascination with these kinds of experience. EvenÂ if we can ultimately give a scientific explanation for their occurrences, these experiences are soÂ unlike our normal experiences of events in time that they certainly give rise to a sense of wonder.</p>\n<p>I suspect, though, that regardless of any explanation of the cause of these experiences (be thatÂ scientific or otherwise) we would do well to take some advice from a reasonably well-knownÂ quotation that I gather is due to Gerard Way(6): âOne day your life will flash before your eyes. MakeÂ sure it&#8217;s worth watchingâ.</p>\n<p>1 van Lommel, P. van Wees,, R. Meyers,V and Elfferich, I. 2001. âNear-death experience inÂ survivors of cardiac arrest: a prospective study in the Netherlandsâ, Lancet, 358, 2039-45, p. 2041<br />\n2 Owens, J.E., Cook, E.W., Stevenson, I. 1990. âFeatures of &#8220;near-death experience&#8221; in relation toÂ whether or not patients were near deathâ, Lancet, 336, 1175-1177<br />\n3 Again, see the 2001 Lancet piece.<br />\n4 See Mobbs, D. and Watt, C. 2011. âThere is nothing paranormal about near-death experiences:Â how neuroscience can explain seeing bright lights, meeting the dead, or being convinced you areÂ one of themâ, Trends in Cognitive Science, 15, 447-9<br />\n5 <a href="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" class="autohyperlink" title="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" target="_blank">ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56</a><br />\n6 <a href="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" class="autohyperlink" title="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" target="_blank">www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:41:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"Timely Wins Most Promising Startup 2012!";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"http://time.ly/timely-wins-most-promising-startup-2012/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"http://time.ly/timely-wins-most-promising-startup-2012/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 26 Oct 2012 20:25:39 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=19279";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:301:"It doesn&#8217;t seem that long ago when the sleeves were first rolled up, the first hands hands were shaken, a name was chosen and a plan was put in motion to launch Timely and the event calendar network, in fact &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/timely-wins-most-promising-startup-2012/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1857:"<p>It doesn&#8217;t seem that long ago when the sleeves were first rolled up, the first hands hands were shaken, a name was chosen and a plan was put in motion to launch Timely and the event calendar network, in fact it was only 10 months ago to be exact and in that short amount of time we&#8217;ve made tremendous progress andÂ evidentlyÂ demonstrated some<img class=" wp-image-19280 alignright" title="photo-2-e1351267936580-764x1024" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/photo-2-e1351267936580-764x1024.jpeg" alt="" width="321" height="430" />Â serious potential to some people who know a thing or two about tech startups. Last night Timely was honoured with the <strong>Most Promising New Startup Award for 2012</strong> at the <a href="http://www.kast.com/kast-news/spirit-innovation-awards-oct-25">KAST Spirit of Innovation Awards</a>.</p>\n<p>This is our first award as a technology startup and it gives us a great boost of confidence to know that we&#8217;re on the right track and making an impression. Â Startup life is filled with high-highs and low-lows but when you&#8217;ve got the support of your community and the validation of your industry it can make all the difference. We&#8217;ve come a long way this year, taking the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/all-in-one-event-calendar/">All-in-One Event Calendar</a> through some major feature and performance upgrades and growing our plugin downloads to nearly 270k with no sign of stopping.Â Â But don&#8217;t worry, we won&#8217;t let this award go to our heads, what we&#8217;ve achieved so far is just the beginning and we intend to make good on being &#8220;the most promising startup of 2012&#8243; (and beyond). Â Thanks to all who have believed in us and championed our product this first year and we can&#8217;t wait to show you what&#8217;s in-store next. Tally-ho!</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"http://time.ly/timely-wins-most-promising-startup-2012/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:53:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39:"Featured Event: Wordcamp Vancouver 2012";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:63:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 22 Oct 2012 20:50:15 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Featured Events";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Apple";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"meet-up";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Wordcamp";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Wordpress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=18556";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:335:"Last week we had the pleasure of attending our first Wordcamp here in Vancouver and it was an awesome experience. Wordcamps (for the uninitiated) are meet-ups held all over the world bringing WordPress-ers of all skill levels and interests together &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2651:"<p><img class=" wp-image-18559 alignleft" title="wordpress_icons1" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/wordpress_icons1.jpg" alt="" width="270" height="247" />Last week we had the pleasure of attending our first<a href="http://2012.vancouver.wordcamp.org/"> Wordcamp here in Vancouver</a> and it was an awesome experience. <a href="http://central.wordcamp.org/">Wordcamps</a> (for the uninitiated) are meet-ups held all over the world bringing WordPress-ers of all skill levels and interests together for day long or multi-day events to talk about everything from code, to design, to business management, to freelance etiquette and of course the future of the wonderful WordPress publishing platform.</p>\n<p>The importance of the these events to the WordPress community cannot be overstated, in fact the rise and popularity of WordPress to become, arguably <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/jjcolao/2012/09/05/the-internets-mother-tongue/">the web&#8217;s most dominant publishing platform</a> can be largely attributed to Wordcamps and <a href="http://wordpress.meetup.com/">WordPress meet-up</a> events happening around the globe that bring people together to share ideas, solve problems and advance their overall understanding of what is possible in the WP universe.</p>\n<p>It may seem strange to think of something that is essentially a big block of programming code garnering an international cult-like following but beautiful technology attracts a crowd (witness the<a href="http://theweek.com/article/index/229766/5-signs-that-apple-is-a-cult"> kingdom of Apple</a>). Â With WordPress as an open-source, contributive platform this is especially the case.Wordpress is made and largely governed by it&#8217;s community of users and programmers, no single entity really controls it (although the company <a href="http://automattic.com/">Automattic</a>Â ownsÂ <a href="www.wordpress.com">wordpress.com</a> and manages the central code contributions to <a href="http://wordpress.org/">WordPress</a>). It is quiet possibly the web&#8217;s greatest example of a sophisticated, democratized communication platform, where the tools, the processes and the culture evolve in an open forum for all to see and participate in. It really is a beautiful thing.</p>\n<p>At Wordcamp Vancouver we caught up with one of the main organizers <a href="https://twitter.com/mor10">Morten Rand-Hendriksen</a> to talk about why Wordcamps make the WordPress world go around.</p>\n<div class="entry-content-asset"><iframe width="940" height="529" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/KU1PWcdCMBc?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"http://time.ly/featured-event-wordcamp-vancouver-2012/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:56:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Time Well Spent";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 10 Oct 2012 23:12:21 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Antiphon";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"experiences";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"family";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"happiness";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=16223";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:286:"âTime well spentââsuch a familiar phrase. If someone said it to you, youâd know what they were getting at. But where does the expression come from and what does it really mean? The first person (that we know of) to &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/time-well-spent/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6296:"<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-16411" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="Fans at rock show" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/fans-at-a-concert-300x224.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="224" />âTime well spentââsuch a familiar phrase. If someone said it to you, youâd know what they were getting at. But where does the expression come from and what does it <em>really</em> mean?</p>\n<p>The first person (that we know of) to speak of <em>spending</em> time, in the way that one might spend a currency, was Antiphon (c. 480-411 BC), and as weâll see in future posts we owe a lot of our thinking about time to Greek writers and philosophers of this period. We donât know too much about Antiphon, (although Â this Wikpedia entry gives us a good start: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiphon_(person">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiphon_(person</a>)</p>\n<p>Anyway, what interests us here is not so much who Antiphon was, as what he said. The expression that concerns us is this: <em>the most costly outlay is the outlay of time</em>. Now, we normally say that the sorts of things that we can <em>spend</em> are resourcesâthings like energy, money or effort. So a literal reading of this expression might suggest that time <em>is</em> a resource. But if thatâs right, then time is going to be very much unlike other resources.</p>\n<p>For one thing, once itâs gone, time <em>cannot</em> be replaced, unlike money or effort. Nor can we find a âsubstituteâ as we might try to for a natural resource, like oil or coal. Quite unlike all of our other resources, we canât control the <em>rate</em> at which we use up time nor can we store it.</p>\n<p>In fact, things get stranger still! If I spend some money, or energy, then in return I get something back. If I spend my money, I get <img class="alignright  wp-image-16414" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="usr_150707215554_hour-glass" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/usr_150707215554_hour-glass.jpg" alt="" width="184" height="227" />goods; if I spend energy, I get some effect. But, if I âspend my timeâ doing something, then I donât <em>seem</em> to <em>get</em> anything. How can this be right if weâre going to claim that timeâs so <em>valuable</em>? If I can spend time without getting anything, surely that makes time our <em>least</em> valuable resource!</p>\n<p>But of course, we <em>do</em> get something when we spend our time on something. We get experiences. Experiences can be valuable. In fact, experiences can be <em>incredibly </em>valuableâjust think of the ones that matter most to you. So, timeâs a resource that you canât store, that you canât replace and that you canât control. And youâre spending it on experiences every waking second of every single day of your life.</p>\n<p><img class="size-medium wp-image-16413 alignleft" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="stock-footage-people-walking-jogging-fishing-at-a-park-by-the-beach-at-sunset-in-hawaii" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/stock-footage-people-walking-jogging-fishing-at-a-park-by-the-beach-at-sunset-in-hawaii-e1349910092994.jpg" alt="" width="249" height="224" /></p>\n<p>Now if time is such a valuable resource, then what <em>should</em> we do with it? Are there particular sorts of behavior that are <em>better</em> uses ofour time than others? Recent research suggests that there are. Some research suggests that long working hours are negatively correlated with emotional satisfaction in adults<a title="" href="#_ftn1">[1]</a> and other research shows that people are happier with <em>experiential</em> purchases than they are with material purchases.<a title="" href="#_ftn2">[2]</a> We also know that time spent engaged in socially connecting activities, such as spending time with family, comprise the happiest parts of the day.<a title="" href="#_ftn3">[3]</a> All of which suggests that we would do well to try to work fewer hours, concentrate our financial resources on experiential purchases and spend more time with our friends and family. Maybe thatâs just common sense.</p>\n<p>But if you want to feel like youâve more time on your handsâthat youâre more <em>time affluent</em>âone recent study suggests that the best thing that you can do is give it away for free.<a title="" href="#_ftn4">[4]</a> The study, led by <a href="https://marketing.wharton.upenn.edu/profile/388/">Cassie Mogilner at the University ofÂ Pennsylvania</a>, found that people who gave up their time to do things for others, found themselves with a feeling of having more time than those who were given <em>free</em> time. Â Just as we have the saying, âyou have to spend money to make moneyâ, this looks to be a case where we need to spend time to make time! Given the connections mentioned above between time affluence and happiness, it looks like it might be a sound investment.</p>\n<div>\n<hr align="left" size="1" width="33%" />\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[1]</a> Kasser, T. and Brown, K 2003. â<a href="http://www.kirkwarrenbrown.vcu.edu/wp-content/pubs/Kasser%20&amp;%20Brown%20TBYT%202004.pdf">On Time, Happiness, and Ecological Footprintsâ</a>, in J. deGraaf (ed.), <em>Take Back your Time: Fighting Overwork and Time Poverty in America</em> (Berrett-Koehler, San Francisco, CA), 107â112</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[2]</a> Van Boven, L. and Gilovich, T. 2003, â<a href="http://dtserv2.compsy.uni-jena.de/ss2012/sozpsy_uj/31119589/content.nsf/Pages/97A6BE3B19E73ABFC1257A4600452E4A/$FILE/Boven%20on%20To%20Do%20or%20to%20Have.pdf">To Do or to Have? That Is the Questionâ</a><em>, Journal of Personality and Social Psychology</em>, 85, 1193â1202</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[3]</a> Csikszentmihalyi, M and Hunter, J. 2003. â<a href="http://www.mendedreality.com/private/docs/CSIKSZENTMIHALYI2003.pdf">Happiness in Everyday Life: The uses of experience sampling</a>â, <em>Journal of Happiness Studies</em>, 4, 185-99</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p><a title="" href="#_ftnref">[4]</a> Molinger, C., Chance, Z. and Norton, D. forthcoming. â<a href="https://marketing.wharton.upenn.edu/files/?whdmsaction=public:main.file&amp;fileID=3722">Giving Time Gives You Time</a>â, <em>Psychological Science</em></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"http://time.ly/time-well-spent/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"Introducing Timelyâs Time Philosopher: Jonathan Tallant";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"http://time.ly/introducing-timelys-time-philosopher-jonathan-tallant/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"http://time.ly/introducing-timelys-time-philosopher-jonathan-tallant/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 05 Oct 2012 22:14:57 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=11852";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:292:"Time. What is Time? How do we measure it? Where does it come from? Is it outside of us or just in our heads? If a clock ticks in the forest and no one&#8217;s around, does it really tell the &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/introducing-timelys-time-philosopher-jonathan-tallant/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2571:"<p><img class=" wp-image-15471 alignleft" title="spiral-clock" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/spiral-clock-300x294.jpg" alt="" width="240" height="235" />Time. What is <em>Time</em>? How do we measure it? Where does it come from? Is it outside of us or just in our heads? If a clock ticks in the forest and no one&#8217;s around, does it really tell the time? What is a <em>good time</em>? What is a <em>bad time</em>? Getting a little too deep for you? Well you may think that a calendar software developer has no business waxing philosophical about something as nebulous as time but you&#8217;d be wrong! We&#8217;re time geeks here to the extreme. We like to look at time from all sorts of different angles, and we love talking with people who do the same, that&#8217;s why were excited to introduce a our new guest blogger, Jonathan Tallant!</p>\n<p>Jonathan is a time philosopherÂ at the <a href="http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/index.aspx">University of<em>Â </em>Nottingham</a>. That&#8217;s right. A <em><a href="http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/philosophy/people/jonathan.tallant">Time Philosopher</a>.</em>Â As far as we&#8217;re concerned that&#8217;s just<img class="alignright  wp-image-15470" title="a5oxpox2wlef9g3uspap" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/a5oxpox2wlef9g3uspap-300x225.jpeg" alt="" width="240" height="180" /> one step down from <a href="http://images.epilogue.net/users/nathie/BadGuySorcererApril72.jpg">Time Sorcerer</a> and well above your common <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwnjENpIyq0">Time Bandit</a>. Alas Jonathan is not involved in the direct manipulation of time per say but he does posit a variety of fascinating theories and themes on how humansÂ perceiveÂ and experience time. As such we asked him to help us explore the concept of time experience as it relates to events, great and small. His first guest post appears next week and we&#8217;ll be hounding him for more whenever he&#8217;s got the (wait for it) &#8211; <strong><em>time!Â </em></strong></p>\n<p>Check out some of Jonathan&#8217;s videos on YouTube and stay tuned for next week&#8217;s post in <a href="http://time.ly/category/thoughts-on-time/">Thoughts on Time.</a></p>\n<div class="entry-content-asset"><iframe width="940" height="529" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/zw6hS_gy9MY?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<div class="entry-content-asset"><iframe width="940" height="529" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/1EGDCh75SpQ?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"http://time.ly/introducing-timelys-time-philosopher-jonathan-tallant/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:41:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Calendar Stories: Jacksonopolis";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 01 Oct 2012 15:30:33 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Calendar Stories";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=14066";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:317:"One of the things we love here at Timely is coming across calendar users who really understand the potential of our All-in-One Event Calendar plugin to connect communities via cross-calendar sharing and make it easy for people to find the &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5513:"<p>One of the things we love here at Timely is coming across calendar users who really understand the potential of our All-in-One Event Calendar plugin to connect communities via cross-calendar sharing and make it easy for people to find the events they care about. That&#8217;s why starting this month we&#8217;re launching a new monthly blog series called <strong>Calendar Stories</strong>Â to highlight some of the best examples of our plugin being used around the world.</p>\n<p><img class="size-medium wp-image-14069 alignleft" title="jacksonopolis1" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/jacksonopolis1-300x300.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="300" />A few weeks ago the folks over at <a href="http://www.jacksonopolis.com/" target="_blank">Jacksonopolis.com</a>Â Tweeted us to show off their new community calendar set-up. Jacksonopolis is setting itself up to be the go-to source for community news and events for <a href="https://maps.google.ca/maps?q=Jackson+Michigan&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=0x883d25593e337b6b:0xce45a6328e9bd551,Jackson,+MI,+USA&amp;gl=ca&amp;ei=pfhlUJPmH6TYigKh3ICwCg&amp;ved=0CMYBELYD">Jackson, Michigan</a>. Co-founder and CEO of Jacksonopolis <a href="https://www.facebook.com/davidbuchanan">David Buchanan</a> was kind enough to answer some questions about how they&#8217;ve been using Timely&#8217;s All-in-One plugin to power their events calendar and why it&#8217;s important for communities like Jackson to have a unified events platform to stay informed and connected.</p>\n<h4>Could you describe what Jacksonopolis is and how it came to be?</h4>\n<p><em>Jacksonopolis showcases people, places, culture, and community in Jackson, Michigan. We came to life because of a dire need for our community to build pride, focus creativity and grow new economic sectors. Our city has been misrepresented for some time so our team is working hard to highlight the things which make our town so great. All content is submitted by the community and the site is supported by the generous local business and organizations that continue to make it great<strong><strong>.</strong></strong></em></p>\n<h4>What prompted the need for a more networked community events calendar?</h4>\n<p><em>Weâve run a new media company, Coefficient Media, since 2007 building websites and the community members came to us begging to build a well designed and usable central place for Jackson. For over 4 years we used our network to gather information and hold open meetings with the community to find their needs and wants. This is one of the reasons we love social networking; Itâs tools like Facebook, Twitter and web portals, which enable communication and interactivity all around us. We set our focus to foster certain interactions, how to influence and share different events with friends, family, community members and leaders to have a more organized online experience.</em><strong><strong><br />\n</strong></strong></p>\n<h4>Why is a complete events listing important for your community?</h4>\n<div id="attachment_14071" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-14071 " title="Jacksonopolis2" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Jacksonopolis2-300x300.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /><p class="wp-caption-text">A local Jackson community event.</p></div>\n<p><em>While the idea of events listings and calendars are not new to a local community, we want to take it to the next level. Â Technology isÂ </em><em>changing the way we interact with our local community and we feel the need to connect more than ever. So much is happening all around us we need to calendar feature events, make them easy to share, intuitive to navigate, and able to subscribe to categories.</em></p>\n<p><em>Our goal is to tear down the existing roadblocks and let the community share and connect organically through the use of their everyday tools, like social media.<strong><strong>Â </strong></strong></em></p>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h4>Why did you choose Timely&#8217;s All-in-One Events Calendar for the job?</h4>\n<ol>\n<li><em>Social integration. Â We want the events to live in on Facebook along with being associated with our website.</em>\n<p><div id="attachment_14070" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><img class="size-medium wp-image-14070" title="jacksonopolis3" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/jacksonopolis3-300x223.jpeg" alt="" width="300" height="223" /><p class="wp-caption-text"><em>The Jacksonopolis team hard at work.</em></p></div></li>\n<li><em>Cross Calendar Sharing. Â We build a lot of calendars and the ability to link data from one to another is amazing. Â With Timely, the calendar we built for the Artâs Council and the calendar for the Young Professionals network will have the same unified data structure!</em></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>So what&#8217;s next for Jacksonopolis? David says they&#8217;re planning on syncing filtered event data between various community calendars all using the Ai1EC to create an events network powered by individuals and businesses across their region (that&#8217;s exactly what we designed it for!). Congrats to David and his team for building a great looking site with an awesome organizational mandate. If you live, work (or travel) in the Jackson MI area, <a href="http://Jacksonopolis.com" class="autohyperlink" title="http://Jacksonopolis.com" target="_blank">Jacksonopolis.com</a> should be your first stop for news and events.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"http://time.ly/calendar-stories-jacksonopolis/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:53:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"Featured Event: Seattle Startup Day 2012";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"http://time.ly/featured-event-seattle-startup-day-2012/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"http://time.ly/featured-